        <div style="float: left; width: 490px;">
         <table style="width: 475px; border-color: #000000; border-width: 0px; border-style: solid;">
          <tbody>
           <tr>
            <td>
             <p style="color: 1589ff;">
              <span style="font-family: times new roman; color: #2d6cc0; font-size: medium;">
               <img alt="Nobel Prize Winner to Join UC Riverside Faculty" class="img_L" height="108" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," title="3newgrants"/>
               Nobel Prize Winner to Join UC Riverside Faculty
               <br/>
              </span>
             </p>
             <span class="date">
              <span style="color: #d36006;">
               July 02, 2018
              </span>
             </span>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             Richard Schrock, a Nobel Prize-winning chemist and UC Riverside alumnus, will join the faculty in UCR's College of Natural and Agricultural Sciences in September 2018. He will be the inaugural George K. Helmkamp Founder's Chair in Chemistry, named after one of the founding faculty members of UCR's Department of Chemistry.&amp;nbsp
             <a class="Morelink" href="https://ucrtoday.ucr.edu/54406">
              Read More
             </a>
             <img alt="test" height="10" size="1" src="/images/design6/dividerline.jpg" title="test" width="450"/>
            </td>
           </tr>
           <tr>
            <td>
             <p style="color: 1589ff;">
              <span style="font-family: times new roman; color: #2d6cc0; font-size: medium;">
               <img alt="DOE Office of Science Graduate Student Research Program Award" class="img_L" height="108" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," title="3newgrants"/>
               DOE Office of Science Graduate Student Research Program Award
               <br/>
              </span>
             </p>
             <span class="date">
              <span style="color: #d36006;">
               June 06, 2018
              </span>
             </span>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             Victor Fung receives the DOE Office of Science Graduate Student Research Program (SCGSR) award. Victor is a third-year graduate student in De-en Jiang's group; his research focuses on computational understanding of surface catalysis. The SCGSR award will fund Victor for a six-month stay at Oak Ridge National Laboratory to conduct part of his dissertation research with a staff scientist there.
             <img alt="test" height="10" size="1" src="/images/design6/dividerline.jpg" title="test" width="450"/>
            </td>
           </tr>
           <tr>
            <td>
             <p style="color: 1589ff;">
              <span style="font-family: times new roman; color: #2d6cc0; font-size: medium;">
               <img alt="Publication is Highly Ranked by the Editorial Team of Angewandte Chemie" class="img_L" height="108" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," title="3newgrants"/>
               Publication is Highly Ranked by the Editorial Team of Angewandte Chemie
               <br/>
              </span>
             </p>
             <span class="date">
              <span style="color: #d36006;">
               May 14, 2018
              </span>
             </span>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             An international team led by Prof. Val Vullev, with Prof. Greg Beran overseeing the computational studies and Dr. Dan Borchardt providing the 2D NMR analysis, discovers unprecedentedly large effects of molecular electric dipoles on charge transfer, and develops an approach for quantifying such effects. Lowering medium polarity allows them to demonstrate enhancement of electron transfer (ET) along dipoles while completely suppressing ET against them. While medium polarity is essential for mediating ET, it also quenches dipole-generated electric fields. Molecular designs, developed by the team, attain a fine balance between these two opposing effects and permit dipole-mediated ET in hydrocarbon media. It sets an importance foundation for developing energy and electronic materials and devices. These findings are published in the link below. Angewandte Chemie, and the reviewers ranked the work as "very important" and "highly important."  According to the journal editors, less than 10% of the manuscripts receive such positive reviews, and they selected it to be published as a "Hot Paper".&amp;nbsp
             <a class="Morelink" href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/anie.201802637">
              Read More
             </a>
             <img alt="test" height="10" size="1" src="/images/design6/dividerline.jpg" title="test" width="450"/>
            </td>
           </tr>
           <tr>
            <td>
             <p style="color: 1589ff;">
              <span style="font-family: times new roman; color: #2d6cc0; font-size: medium;">
               <img alt="UC Riverside UCCS 2018" class="img_L" height="108" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," title="3newgrants"/>
               UC Riverside UCCS 2018
               <br/>
              </span>
             </p>
             <span class="date">
              <span style="color: #d36006;">
               May 14, 2018
              </span>
             </span>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             Several graduate students from UC Riverside had a major impact on the 3rd Annual University of California Chemical Symposium, which was held at the UCLA Lake Arrowhead Conference Center and brings together graduate students and postdoctoral fellows from the entire UC system. The UCCS 2018 drew over 100 graduate student and post-doctoral attendees in addition to keynote speakers Prof. Adam Veige from the University of Florida and Prof. Carrie Partch from UC Santa Cruz. The Royal Society of Chemistry sponsored poster prizes in six subject areas and two of these were claimed by UCR graduate students.&amp;nbsp
             <a class="Morelink" href="http://chem.ucr.edu/news/UCCS_2018_News.pdf">
              Read More
             </a>
             <img alt="test" height="10" size="1" src="/images/design6/dividerline.jpg" title="test" width="450"/>
            </td>
           </tr>

             <p style="color: 1589ff;">
              <span style="font-family: times new roman; color: #2d6cc0; font-size: medium;">
               <img alt="Dr. Jessy Lemieux - Assistant Professor at San Bernardino Valley College" class="img_L" height="108" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," title="3newgrants"/>
               Dr. Jessy Lemieux - Assistant Professor at San Bernardino Valley College
               <br/>
              </span>
             </p>
             <span class="date">
              <span style="color: #d36006;">
               September 23, 2016
              </span>
             </span>
             <br/>
             <br/>
             Jessy Lemieux earned his PhD at UC-Riverside performing experimental studies on thermal decomposition kinetics of molecules relevant to combustion and semiconductor chemical vapor deposition processes in the research group of Dr. Jingsong Zhang. Jessy is a passionate educator who was twice recognized as Teaching Assistant of the Year in the UCR Chemistry Department and now is an Assistant Professor of Chemistry at San Bernardino Valley College since 2015 where he teaches Introductory and Organic Chemistry.&amp;nbsp
             <a class="Morelink" href="https://www.valleycollege.edu/academic-career-programs/degrees-certificates/chemistry/faculty.php">
              Read More
             </a>
